The food is really good—not 100% authentic, but really good. Dine-in portion sizes are more than ample. Take out, not so much—more like showing up to dinner after everyone's eaten. The dining area is cozy, not comfy—chat while you eat then get out. This is not a Micheline dining experience, but you will be served and your food will be good. Ordering over the phone or online is a complete NIGHTMARE. I hesitate saying this because I like the food—good neighborhood food spots are hard to come by and even harder to keep.  However,  there's an older woman working FOH—answers the phone taking orders, and barks at guests—left to only her antics, this place would have been closed by a mutiny, long ago. I understand cultural differences and  running businesses, but there have been times when we see her there and we turn around, no mattter the hunger or the craving...sad truth. This has now become, more frequently than not and it make me angry and disappointed. If Freda's is in the restaurant business for the short haul, make the money then head out, I'd say they're on point. If they're looking to be a respected and longstanding neighborhood establishment, make some adjustments to your FOH (btw, we usually avoid her by going in early on Sundays). Favorite dishes...oxtails, roti, baked chicken, collards, candied yams, callallo, carrot cake, and the sorrel—nyam nyam!

We stopped by Freda's today in search of good authentic jerk chicken. We got jerk chicken, chicken roti and jerk shrimp. We have been to many "Caribbean /Jamaican" restaurants / food trucks in NYC and this place is definitely above the average. Chicken roti and jerk chicken was pretty good, jerk shrimp was just alright. Non of the items was spicy. You can ask for a special jerk sauce on the side that is similar to what you would get in Jamaica's jerk cafes. But even the sauce is americanized to cater to people who can't handle spices. Again food was good for NYC, but don't expect it to be authentic like in Jamaica.

WOW! While in the area, and hungry, my search for a restaurant resulted in discovering "Freda's". It's a small place (be careful...you may walk right past it), but quaint. My waitress was very pleasant and juggled several tables in as smooth and professional a manner as I've ever seen.  The menu is packed with an assortment of both Caribbean and southern-style selections, including jerk chicken, oxtails, brown-stewed chicken and a variety of fish. There is also yams, rice & peas, mac & cheese, collard greens, etc.  My brown-stewed chicken was quite delicious and the yams were equally as enjoyable. The mac & cheese noodles were a bit overcooked, but did have good flavor. The prices were reasonable and the portions were adequate.  I'm rarely in this part of Manhattan, but if I were to return, Freda's would be on my list for dining. I recommend it!

Meeting an old friend in the middle, I took the train uptown to 110th and she took the train downtown. She has a Caribbean family connection so I thought Freda's would be good. It was perfect! I ordered the Oxtail - sumptuous, meaty, slightly sweet. Touch of coconut flavor in the rice and red beans. Eleanor, Freda's daughter, suggested the calaloo (sp?) and I chose the mac n' cheese. Yum and yum! Good jerk chicken roti, yet for me it's Oxtail that will keep me going uptown.
